==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic, perhaps from Indo-European ''*ghoilos'' ‘frothing, tempestuous, wanton’.  Cognate with Old Saxon [[gel|gēl]] (Dutch [[geil]] ‘salacious, lustful’), Old High German [[geil]] (German [[geil]] ‘lustful’), Old Norse [[geiligr]] ‘beautiful’.  The IE root may also be the source of Lithuanian [[gailus|gailùs]] ‘sharp, biting’, Russian [[зело]] ‘very’.

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/ga:l/}}

===Adjective===
{{Unicode|'''gāl'''}}
# [[wanton]], [[lustful]]; [[wicked]]
#: ''And se Iouis wearð swa swyðe gal þæt he on his agenre swyster gewifode.'' And Jove became so depraved that he married his own sister.  (Wulfstan, ''De Falsis Deis'')

